Horace, following up the figure of the runaway soldier, apo- strophizes his imagined captor. ‘He is a born slave—keep him—set him to shepherd or to plough, or do your bid- ding on the sea.' In plain language, ‘ of such stuff are made not “ viri boni ’⁹ or philosophers, but those who pursue the menial and money-making profes— sions.' The ‘ mereator‚’ as usual, is the type of eager pursuit of wealth; see especially Od. 3. 24. 40 n. and Epp. 1. 1. 45 foll. Note the philosophical con- tempt for industrial life.
